<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910104-0054</DOCNO><DOCID>910104-0054.</DOCID><HL>   Group to Vote Stake   In Graphic Scanning   For BellSouth Deal</HL><DATE>01/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C11</SO><CO>   BLS GSCC</CO><IN>TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A group led by Mario Gabelli, a New Yorkinvestment manager, said it will vote its shares in favor ofAtlanta-based BellSouth Corp.'s proposed acquisition ofGraphic Scanning Corp., a cellular telephone and pagingservices provider based in Englewood, N.J., for $5.50 ashare, or about $180 million.   The group said in a Securities and Exchange Commissionfiling that it agreed with BellSouth, a regional Belltelephone company, last Sunday that it wouldn't deposit anyof its Graphic Scanning stock in a voting trust and that itwould vote its stake for the merger. An exception may occur,however, if another merger proposal emerges. The Gabelligroup last reported a 44.88% stake in Graphic Scanning.</LP><TEXT>   In national over-the-counter trading yesterday, GraphicScanning shares closed at $4.625, up 6.25 cents. In New YorkStock Exchange composite trading, BellSouth shares closed at$53.875, down 50 cents.   BellSouth's BellSouth Enterprises unit and GraphicScanning said jointly last Monday that they had reached theagreement for BellSouth Enterprises to acquire GraphicScanning.   With deadlines on debt payments looming, Graphic Scanningsaid in mid-December that it was holding talks with apotential buyer. The company provides its services in theU.S. and Britain.</TEXT></DOC>